Image Matrix
============

The ``image_matrix()`` function arranges a set of images in a grid.

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 8-18

.. code-block:: default



    from PIL import Image
    import numpy as np

    from lets_plot import *
    from lets_plot.bistro.im import *

    LetsPlot.setup_html()








.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 20-23

.. code-block:: default


    img = Image.open('rock_formation.png')








.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 24-33

.. code-block:: default


    rows, cols = 3, 3
    matrix = np.empty((rows, cols), dtype=object)
    for r in range(rows):
        for c in range(cols):
            w, h = 128 + 64 * c, 128 + 64 * r
            matrix[r][c] = np.asarray(img.resize((w, h)))
    image_matrix(matrix, norm=False, scale=.5)

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 36-41

``geom_image()``
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

The ``image_matrix()`` function uses ``geom_image()`` under the hood, so
you might want to look at the following example.

.. GENERATED FROM PYTHON SOURCE LINES 44-45

.. code-block:: default


    ggplot() + geom_image(image_data=np.asarray(img))




.. raw:: html

    <div class="output_subarea output_html rendered_html output_result">

       <head>
           <script type="text/javascript" data-lets-plot-script="library" src="https://dl.bintray.com/jetbrains/lets-plot/lets-plot-2.0.1.min.js"></script>
       </head>
       <body>
              <div id="4OLcMN"></div>
       <script type="text/javascript" data-lets-plot-script="plot">
           var plotSpec={
    'mapping':{
    },
    'data_meta':{
    },
    'kind':"plot",
    'scales':[],
    'layers':[{
    'geom':"image",
    'mapping':{
    'xmin':"xmin",
    'ymin':"ymin",
    'xmax':"xmax",
    'ymax':"ymax"
    },
    'data_meta':{
    },
    'href':"data:image/png;base64,",
    'data':{
    'xmin':[-0.5],
    'ymin':[-0.5],
    'xmax':[639.5],
    'ymax':[426.5]
    }
    }]
    };
           var plotContainer = document.getElementById("4OLcMN");
           LetsPlot.buildPlotFromProcessedSpecs(plotSpec, -1, -1, plotContainer);
       </script>
       </body>
    </html>
